    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-30T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-30T11:00:00-05:00" n="900"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d900">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 E.W./11–3044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-30T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 30, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 30—12:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10575. Personal for the Secretary. When I was in Washington I discussed within
                    the Department, with McCloy<note n="26" xml:id="d900fn26">John J. McCloy,
                        Assistant Secretary of War.</note> in the War Department, with Francis
                        Biddle<note n="27" xml:id="d900fn27">Attorney General.</note> in the
                    Department of Justice and the President problems relating to war crimes.</p>
                <p>Since returning here I have talked with Mr. Herbert Pell who represents us on
                    United Nations Commission for the Investigation of War Crimes. He tells me that
                    the situation in that Commission at the present time makes it necessary that he
                    go home to report.</p>
                <p>I believe it would be wise to call him back in order that we may coordinate our
                    policies in this field and particularly as there are decisions pending here
                    about which you should be promptly and completely informed.<note n="28"
                        xml:id="d900fn28">Mr. Pell’s travel authorization to the United States and
                        return was transmitted by the Department’s telegram No. 10102, December 2,
                        1944, 3 p.m. (740.00116 EW/11–3044).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
